II. Codex Β. A vellum MS. of the middle of the fifteenth centiuy, pre- served in the British Museum, Bibl. Rey. 8 D. ix. The text agrees in its main features with that of A. It has, however, capitulationes for the second and third books, which do not exist in A, and a paragraph in the middle of the second book (ii. 20). These have been introduced into the present work (pp. 100, 188, 131). It also contains a recital of the names of St. Columba’s twelve (liscililes, and of his immediate kinsmen. This appendage, which comes without a break immediately after the text in the manuscript, is not an integral part of the work; but as it is evidently very ancient and trustworthy, it forms the subject of Additional Note A (pp. 245-247) in the present work. The manuscript wants about a quaternio at the beginning, and commences abruptly in the middle ofi. 3 (25). This defect is of old standing, for the name chmley, written at the foot of the first page, is the signature of John, Lord Lumley⁰‚ who died in 1609. Otherwise, the manuscript is in unexceptionable preser- vation; the vellum clean, and the writing distinct. The capitals are large and massive, in red and blue alternately3 those at the beginning of sections or paragraphs smaller, but coloured in like manner: the tituli are in rubrio.
